1
00:00:00,260 --> 00:00:07,400
In this video we are going to learn primitive obsession and strongly typed IDs in domain driven design.

2
00:00:07,520 --> 00:00:11,480
So let me start with the what is primitive obsession?

3
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:18,980
Primitive obsession is a code smell where primitives like string, integer, grid are used for the domain

4
00:00:18,980 --> 00:00:22,520
concepts, leading to ambiguity and errors.

5
00:00:22,880 --> 00:00:30,320
For instance, using a grid or string for an order ID, customer ID, or product ID makes it easy to

6
00:00:30,320 --> 00:00:35,330
mix these identifiers up as they are all of the same type.

7
00:00:35,330 --> 00:00:39,230
So how can we solve these primitive obsession?

8
00:00:39,860 --> 00:00:43,070
The solution is using strongly typed IDs.

9
00:00:43,460 --> 00:00:46,190
So now let me answer these questions.

10
00:00:46,190 --> 00:00:49,070
What is strongly typed IDs pattern?

11
00:00:49,070 --> 00:00:55,490
Strongly typed IDs involves creating distinct types for each kind of ID in your domain.

12
00:00:55,730 --> 00:00:59,450
This makes your code more expressive and less error prone.

13
00:01:00,020 --> 00:01:07,670
It clarifies which type of ID is expected and prevents accidentally using one type of ID where another

14
00:01:07,670 --> 00:01:09,620
type of ID is intended.

15
00:01:09,650 --> 00:01:15,980
So now let me show you how can we use strongly type ID pattern into the orderitem?

16
00:01:15,980 --> 00:01:20,660
Please open the Visual Studio and go to the models and Orderitem.

17
00:01:20,660 --> 00:01:26,990
If you go to Orderitem and go to the constructor of the Orderitem, you can see the first two parameters

18
00:01:26,990 --> 00:01:34,550
are order id and product ID and when we are creating Orderitem, it is very easy to pass wrong IDs into

19
00:01:34,550 --> 00:01:35,570
constructors.

20
00:01:35,570 --> 00:01:42,110
That means you can create Orderitem with the wrong order ID and product ID, you can simply replace

21
00:01:42,110 --> 00:01:44,750
wrong ids them into the parameter.

22
00:01:44,750 --> 00:01:50,300
Instead of sending order ID, you can send product ID in here and send order ID in here.

23
00:01:50,300 --> 00:01:51,200
So we call.

24
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:53,510
This problem is a primitive obsession.

25
00:01:53,510 --> 00:01:58,580
And in order to solve this problem we can define strongly type IDs.

26
00:01:58,580 --> 00:02:07,250
That means instead of using the grid for order id, I can create an order id type and we can pass the

27
00:02:07,250 --> 00:02:10,520
order id parameter into Orderitem constructor.

28
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:15,740
And at the same way we can create product id type for product id definition.

29
00:02:15,740 --> 00:02:20,210
By this way we can avoid the setting value by mistake.

30
00:02:20,390 --> 00:02:24,710
So using the strong type IDs giving lots of benefits.

31
00:02:24,710 --> 00:02:27,320
The first benefit is type safety.

32
00:02:27,320 --> 00:02:34,940
Mistakenly passing a product ID where an order ID is expected is now a compile time error, and we cannot

33
00:02:34,940 --> 00:02:40,040
pass the order ID instead of the product id with a type saved values.

34
00:02:40,040 --> 00:02:42,530
And the second benefit is readability.

35
00:02:42,530 --> 00:02:47,300
The constructor clearly indicates that what type of id is required.

36
00:02:47,300 --> 00:02:54,470
And lastly, we can say that it is also beneficial for refactoring support IDs can easily distinguish

37
00:02:54,470 --> 00:02:58,730
between these types and adding in refactoring and navigation very easily.

